N:npm-git-install
D:Choose the safest way to consume a Node package from GitHub or another Git remote: direct Git install, SHA pin, private auth, tarball, workspace/file link, or publish-first alternative.
G:npm pnpm yarn bun git github package-management node monorepo private-packages tarball workspace

U[6]:
  Install an unpublished fix or fork from GitHub safely
  Decide whether to use a branch, tag, or SHA for a Git dependency
  Handle private Git package auth and CI constraints
  Choose tarball or `npm pack` artifacts instead of raw Git when packaging is safer
  Prefer workspace or `file:` links for local co-development
  Recommend publish-first/private-registry paths when the dependency becomes durable

S[7]{n,action,details}:
  1,Normalize,Capture package manager, package state, ref type, audience, auth mode, and reproducibility need
  2,Choose mode,Pick one path: direct Git, SHA-pinned Git, private Git, tarball/pack, workspace/file, or publish-first
  3,Decide durability,Prefer publish-first for teammate/CI/production use; treat Git refs as bridges
  4,Pick syntax,Give only the needed npm/pnpm/Yarn/Bun command for the chosen path
  5,Flag auth,Explain SSH vs token vs registry auth and CI parity requirements
  6,Flag build risk,Call out source-build/prepare behavior and monorepo/package-root caveats
  7,Exit plan,State when to replace the temporary Git path with tarball, workspace, or registry publish

R[6]:
  Prefer SHA pins over floating branches whenever a Git dependency will be shared
  Do not recommend committed secrets in manifests or docs
  Use workspace/file links for local co-development, not remote third-party distribution
  Recommend tarball or publish-first when raw Git install is too brittle or too durable for the use case
  Tailor commands to the package manager already in use instead of dumping every syntax variant
  Always leave a clear exit strategy for temporary Git-based dependencies
